{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> μῶν</b>, <br /> <i>adverb</i>, <i>contraction</i> for μὴ οὖν, μῶν χαραδριὸν περνᾷς· [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.BC: Hipponax Iambographus 52: frequently in Trag., Comedy texts, and 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]; usually in questions to which a <i>negative</i> answer is suggested, <b>surely not</b>? μῶν ἄλγος ἴσχει; you are <b>not</b> in pain, <b>are you</b>? [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 734, compare 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hecuba” 676, 754, “Hel.” 1198, 5th c.BC: Achaeus Tragicus 9, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Lysistrata” 69, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Protagoras” 310d.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] —Its origin from μὴ οὖν was forgotten, hence μῶν οὖν..; in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 177, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Andromache” 82 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; μῶν οὖν δῆτα..; [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Plutus” 845: sometimes also μῶν μὴ..; 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedo” 84c, “R.” 505c \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; also μῶν οὐ..; suggesting an affirmative answer, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Supplices” 417, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1729 (Lyric poetry), 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Sophista” 234a, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G20793","accentedUnicode":"μῶν","shortDef":"are you","mediumDef":"are you","stepGloss":"are you","stepTransliteration":"mōn","count":0,"_step_Type":"word"}]}